Egypt announces 2 new human infections of bird flu
-----------------------------------------------
Two new human infections of bird flu were reported in Egypt on Sunday [2
Apr 2006], as the country is battling the highly contagious disease.
Egyptian Minister of Health and Population Hatem el-Gabali announced the 2
new human cases at the Cairo International Airport before departing for
France on a visit.
Two young girls from the governorate of Kafr-el-Sheikh, some 125 km north
of Cairo, had tested positive for bird flu after "playing with infected
poultry," Gabali told reporters at the airport.
The latest infections brought to 7 the number of human cases infected with
the deadly H5N1 strain of bird flu in the populous north African country.
Two of the victims have died, and the others either have recovered or are
still being treated at hospitals.
Egypt reported the outbreak of bird flu in dead poultry on 17 Feb 2006, and
the 1st human bird flu case was announced on 18 Mar 2006.
The Egyptian government has since taken measures to curb the spread of the
fatal disease.
The deadly H5N1 strain has killed over 100 people worldwide since its
latest outbreak in southeast Asia in late 2003, according to the World
Health Organization. Most victims were infected after close contact with
sick birds.
The virus currently can only jump from birds to humans, but scientists fear
that it could mutate into a form capable of passing easily among humans and
thus spark a global human flu pandemic.
